A demographic study has shed further light on the human toll of the Holocaust, when Nazi Germany and its collaborators systematically killed at least six million, or two of every three, European Jews.
“The Jewish population has not returned to what it was before the war,” said Sergio DellaPergola, who conducted the study, “so this is quite impressive to think that the Holocaust of the Jews is still visible. The damage is still visible and not yet recovered to its early dimensions.”
The Jewish community worldwide numbers close to 15 million people, compared with more than 16.5 million in 1939, estimates the World Jewish Population 2020 report.
The annual survey by Hebrew University of Jerusalem draws on data from more than 100 countries to count the “core” population of both ethnic and religious Jews.
