The declining numbers found in most other countries can be attributed to “low birth rates, frequent intermarriage, identificational drift, aging and emigration,” the report found.
DellaPergola, a professor emeritus with Hebrew University of Jerusalem, also noted the “asterisk” of the COVID-19 pandemic, which has “caused dramatic increase in the cases of death and decline in certain parts of the world, slowing (the) rate of growth.”
The survey counts the “core” Jewish population, both by religion and ethnicity. It excluded non-Jewish members of Jewish households, “Jews who also hold another religious identification” or monotheistic religion, “non-Jews of Jewish ancestry,” as well as non-Jews with “family connections to Jews.”
Story continues below
This advertisement has not loaded yet, but your article continues below.
Core population counts help keep the data in line with “comparable” counts in past studies, which go back roughly 40 years, DellaPergola said.
A result of living in contemporary society is “much greater interaction with different groups,” he noted. “We wish to keep a definition which is more or less similar to what the situation was in past generations.”
“If you wish to compare (the Jewish) population of today with a population 50 or 100 years ago, those interactions did not exist very much.”
The study pulls together a vast quantity of different sources to achieve its count. Some samples, such as Canada’s census, can be “remarkably good,” including Jewish status, while the U.S. Jewish population is ascertained with Pew Research data.
Story continues below
