In Europe, the population of Jews is the lowest it’s been in a millennium and further in decline, according to a 2020 study from the Institute for Jewish Policy Research. About nine per cent of the global Jewish population currently lives in the continent whereas, in the late-19th century, it was almost 90 per cent.
Most of the Jewish population in Europe lives in France, the United Kingdom and Germany, with Eastern Europe recording the largest losses, many of the losses following the collapse of the former Soviet Union.
Professor Daniel Stone, who studies Jewish history in the Soviet Union, said a large majority of East European Jews in the postwar Soviet bloc were murdered during the Holocaust, which caused many of the survivors to leave territories they considered hostile.
