“The large Soviet Jewish population in areas that the Germans failed to occupy began to leave in the late 1970s because of discrimination in the U.S.S.R. and the possibility of a better life abroad,” Stone wrote in an email. “Similar stories on a much smaller scale occurred earlier in several Soviet bloc countries.”
Former Polish and Soviet citizens suffered the highest casualties in the Holocaust, according to the U.S. Holocaust Memorial Museum.
Nearly two million Jews have left Eastern Europe in the past 50 years, many in search of better opportunities, according to the study. Western European countries also saw a loss of around 8.5 per cent.
“Throughout history, the inherent weakness of a landless and powerless minority vis-a-vis territorially based societies and their constituted powers often put the Jewish people in a condition of dependency and instability, and translated into powerful ups and downs in the Jewish presence,” state the authors of the Institute for Jewish Policy Research study.
The study, which DellaPergola co-authored, estimated that close to 1.3 million Jews live in Europe, comprising about 0.1 of its population.
With an aging population and a lack of intake of immigrant Jews in the continent — where their numbers were once the strongest — Europe’s population of Jews is expected to further shrink, DellaPergola said.
